          "id": "human-resource-management-201-l02-c2",
          "title": "Learning Transfer: The Critical Challenge",
          "content": "Research indicates that a major challenge in training programs is known as the 'transfer gap.' This term describes the phenomenon where only about 10-20% of the knowledge and skills taught during training sessions are actually utilized in the workplace. Several factors contribute to this gap. For instance, if managers do not provide adequate support, employees may struggle to implement what they have learned. Additionally, without opportunities to practice new skills in a safe environment, it becomes difficult for learners to gain confidence and proficiency. Conflicting demands at work can also make it hard for employees to focus on applying new techniques. Furthermore, if the culture within the organization does not promote innovation or experimentation, employees may feel discouraged from trying out new methods. Poorly designed training that does not reflect real job conditions can exacerbate these issues. To enhance the transfer of learning, it is crucial that training content is closely aligned with the actual tasks employees perform. Providing realistic practice scenarios allows learners to apply their skills effectively. Moreover, when supervisors actively support and encourage the adoption of new behaviors, it significantly increases the likelihood that employees will successfully integrate what they have learned into their daily work routines.\nContext recap: Research indicates that a major challenge in training programs is known as the 'transfer gap.' This term describes the phenomenon where only about 10-20% of the knowledge and skills taught during training sessions are actually utilized in the workplace. Several factors contribute to this gap. For instance, if managers do not provide adequate support, employees may struggle to implement what they have learned. Additionally, without opportunities to practice new skills in a safe environment, it becomes difficult for learners to gain confidence and proficiency.\nWhy this matters: Learning Transfer: The Critical Challenge helps learners in Business connect ideas from Talent Development & Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
