          "content": "In recent years, many top companies like Adobe, Deloitte, and Microsoft have decided to change how they evaluate employee performance. Instead of sticking with the old method of annual performance reviews, which happen just once a year, they have embraced a new approach called continuous performance management. This innovative method focuses on having regular one-on-one check-ins between managers and employees, which can take place every week or every two weeks. These meetings allow for real-time feedback, meaning employees can receive immediate insights about their work and how they can improve.\nMoreover, rather than concentrating solely on past performance, this approach encourages discussions about future goals and personal development. Research has shown that traditional annual reviews can often be discouraging for employees. They tend to focus too much on recent events, a phenomenon known as recency bias, which can lead to unfair evaluations. Additionally, these annual reviews do not significantly enhance employee performance.\nBy adopting continuous feedback, organizations can make timely adjustments to help employees grow and succeed. This ongoing dialogue not only helps in correcting any issues quickly but also strengthens the relationship between managers and their team members. Ultimately, this creates a more positive and supportive work environment where everyone can thrive and reach their full potential.\nContext recap: In recent years, many top companies like Adobe, Deloitte, and Microsoft have decided to change how they evaluate employee performance. Instead of sticking with the old method of annual performance reviews, which happen just once a year, they have embraced a new approach called continuous performance management. This innovative method focuses on having regular one-on-one check-ins between managers and employees, which can take place every week or every two weeks. These meetings allow for real-time feedback, meaning employees can receive immediate insights about their work and how they can improve.\nWhy this matters: The Shift to Continuous Performance Management helps learners in Business connect ideas from Talent Development & Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
