          "title": "360-Degree Feedback",
          "content": "360-degree feedback is a valuable evaluation method that collects performance ratings from a variety of sources surrounding an employee. This feedback comes from supervisors, colleagues, direct reports, and sometimes even customers or external partners. Additionally, the employee provides a self-assessment, which adds another layer to the feedback process. This multi-rater approach is beneficial because it helps to minimize individual bias and offers a more comprehensive view of an employee's behavior across different situations. For instance, a manager might behave differently when interacting with their superiors compared to how they engage with their team members. The 360-degree feedback process captures these variations, providing a fuller understanding of the employee's performance. To ensure the effectiveness of this feedback method, it is important to follow best practices. These include using the feedback primarily for developmental purposes rather than for making compensation decisions. It is also crucial to maintain the anonymity of the raters to encourage honest and constructive feedback. Furthermore, providing professional debriefing sessions can help employees understand the feedback they receive. Finally, following up with a clear development plan is essential to support employees in their growth and improvement based on the feedback they have received.\nContext recap: 360-degree feedback is a valuable evaluation method that collects performance ratings from a variety of sources surrounding an employee. This feedback comes from supervisors, colleagues, direct reports, and sometimes even customers or external partners. Additionally, the employee provides a self-assessment, which adds another layer to the feedback process. This multi-rater approach is beneficial because it helps to minimize individual bias and offers a more comprehensive view of an employee's behavior across different situations.\nWhy this matters: 360-Degree Feedback helps learners in Business connect ideas from Talent Development & Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
